{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4943a3d2-c7f3-4715-a9f2-d6669cadfba3","content":"\n\nUse **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Updates all installed workloads to the latest versions compatible with your current SDK. After an SDK update, this brings workloads (like `maui`) in sync with the new SDK.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Reinstalls the *same versions* of workloads already recorded. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer, SDK-compatible versions.\n\nSince your issue is a **version mismatch** (new SDK, old workloads), `update` is the right choice:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, try a clean restore:\n\n```bash\ndotnet clean && dotnet restore\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"05c5e3e1-9476-46ea-af40-e7fe074cf664","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after an SDK update broke their build.","outputTokens":230},"id":"fe3442ed-bf50-4881-9659-189919564f4a","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:42:54.692Z","parentId":"fe5d6f85-3948-4b04-932c-61d13146f180"}
